data.content:
Here are the three breaking changes and their fixes:

## 1. `Buffer.cs` — `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` is banned in C# 13

C# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` because the compiler-synthesized members (equality, `ToString`, etc.) conflict with inline array layout. **Fix: use a plain `struct`.**

```csharp
[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]
struct Buffer
{
    private int _element0;
}
```

## 2. `Generator.cs` — `stackalloc` in iterator local functions

C# 13 relaxed rules to allow `unsafe` code *inside* iterators, which means the local function is now analyzed as part of the iterator state machine. `stackalloc` is still prohibited in iterators. Previously the local function was compiled separately and escaped this check. **Fix: extract the method out of the iterator.**

```csharp
unsafe class DataGenerator
{
    IEnumerable<int> Generate()
    {
        yield return 1;
        Process();
    }

    static void Process()
    {
        int* p = stackalloc int[10];
        // ... work with pointer
    }
}
```

## 3. `Resolver.cs` — `[]` overload resolution ambiguity

In C# 12, `[]` (empty collection expression) had a single best match for `ReadOnlySpan<int>`. C# 13 changed overload resolution for `params` and span types, making `[]` ambiguous between `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`. **Fix: disambiguate with an explicit type.**

```csharp
class Resolver
{
    static void Process(ReadOnlySpan<int> ros) {}
    static void Process(Span<object> s) {}

    static void Main()
    {
        Process(ReadOnlySpan<int>.Empty);  // explicit target
    }
}
```
